<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Chris Hobbs, Retired Metropolitan Police officer [CST0018]</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Chris Hobbs, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Retired Metropolitan Police officer [CST0018]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I was born in London and have  lived here all my life. I come from a ‘police family’ and have relatives still serving within the force. My last ten years of service were spent working on Operation Trident related matters at UK and Jamaican airports. I have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">, however, extensive contacts throughout the Met which I have retained. I am aware of the frustrations of serving officers and their fears of expressing their concerns to senior managers for fear of repercussions. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">I had personal experience of this when in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> June 2010, I wrote a letter intended for the press which, in addition to criticising Ken Clarke,  also referred extensively to crime figures. This included  the fact that damaging Met police gun crime figures had been excluded from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Met’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> annual report</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">. I sought advice from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Met’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> Press Bureau and was told to submit it to them for scrutiny, which I did.  Despite that, I was hauled before my Chief Superintendent and accused of being 'unprofessional.' There was, so my Federation rep told me, a consider</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">able body of opinion at the top of Scotland Yard that wanted me sacked. However they couldn't as I had formally submitted it internally first.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">13 months later I was forcibly retired albeit with a certificate of exemplary service.  My service record is beyo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">nd reproach and involved football related violence, Asian community tensions and international organised crime networks that blight the black community. Shortly after my retirement I was presented with a ceremonial sword and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">saropa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt"> (scarf) by the UK’s larg</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">est Sikh temple. Despite this record  ‘dissent’ saw the end of my police career and this is the reason why ‘junior’ police officers will remain silent in the face of dubious police practices.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">The officer, James Patrick is likely to be shown as an example o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">f what happens to officers who speak out. His decision to provide a submission to yourselves is extraordinary given the situation in which he finds himself. His book, ‘The Rest is Silence’ is in fact a restrained but disturbing critique of the police refor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">m process. He does not advocate any form of militant action by front line officers, in fact quite the reverse. By forensic examination based on fact, he casts doubt on the process and the motives of those responsible for it. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Met’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">  Commissioner  appear</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">s determined to send a signal to his rank and file that ‘rocking the boat’ will have consequences.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">Below is my submission in respect of crime figures. They are an amalgam of views from front line serving officers who are concerned at the machinations of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">managers in respect of crime figures. There is also comment in respect of the Crime Survey for England and Wales which is also used by police forces to support their mantra of falling crime. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Crime Figures-Are We Being treated As Fools?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">1). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">As a retired </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Met officer, I watched sadly </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">back in Jul</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">y, </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">as a BBC London news report showed a builder’s experience having had all his tools stolen from his van. In a stunning display of efficiency, the next day he received one of the </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Met’s</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> standard ‘Sorry </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">you </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">have be</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">en </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">a victim of crime-case closed.'</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> letters. This in spite of the fact </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">that CCTV footage </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">showed two men removing the tools</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> and placing them in a vehicle where the number </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">plate</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> was clearly </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">visible</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">2). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Why c</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ould this lead to rejoicing at the highest level</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> of the police service</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">? Quite simply because the </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">huge </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">percentage of the public w</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ho won’t bother reporting crime</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">will doubtless increase</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> as a result of either viewing the programme in question or reading newspaper reports. This will  enable</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> the mantra of cr</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ime is going down to continu</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">e to be sung from the rooftops as has been the case with the release of yesterday’s crime figures. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">3). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">At least</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> when Kent police were </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">criticised </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">in the summer </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">for the recording and manipulation of their crime figures, the P</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">olic</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">e </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">rime </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ommisioner</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> and Chief Constable had the decency to </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">state that the situation was </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">un</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">acceptable and would be addressed</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">4). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">But what is the truth around crime figures and how much reliance can we give to figures produced by individual police forces a</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">nd the British Crime </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Survey</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> now renamed the Crime Survey for Englan</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">d and Wales?</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">5). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Shortly after I joined the Met in 1978, I </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">qui</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ckly </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">found out how crime figures could be massaged. Every Saturday there </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">was a</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> local market opposite Southall </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">police station </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">where dippers (pickpockets) would frequently be in action.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">6). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Members of the public used to form queues </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">that stretched </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">outside the police station to report their wallets and purses stolen. Our instructions </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">as constables, </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">were to report the loss as a theft</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> only if the victim</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> actually felt or saw their property being removed. If, as in most cases, they were unaware of the removal of their property, it was recorded as ‘Property Lost in the Street’ thus avoiding an unwelcome </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">addition to the crime figures.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">7).</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Another controversial ‘massage tool’ was in respect of attempted burglaries. When burglars left ‘jemmy marks’ around window and door locks where they had attempted to break in but failed, the classification of the more serious ‘attempted burglary’ would b</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">e downgraded to a more palatable and less serious offence of criminal damage. The same would be true where a window was smashed in an </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">attempt to get at the door or window lock.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> Does this still apply toda</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">y? </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Any inspection worth its salt would unquestionabl</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">y confirm </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">it</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> does</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">8). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Similar issues can be seen in respect of robbery offences.  If an individual surrounded by a group of youths, produces ‘upon request’ his mobile phone for them to ‘have a look at’ and that phone is then snatched from out of his</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> hand, is that offence classified as a robbery or a less serious theft? Even where an assault has taken place, the offence of robbery frequently is ‘do</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">wngraded’ to ‘theft and assault</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> or even just theft. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">9). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">I have even been told by serving officers from </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">two forces that crime victims are even being telephoned and asked to ‘</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">unreport</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’ their previously reported crime in order to reduce the figures. An example of this would be where a car windscreen is found smashed by its owner the next morning and the police</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> assumption is that it just could have been a stone thrown up by a passing car. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">10). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">This is given credenc</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">e when, earlier this year, </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">it was revealed  that Met Police Sapphire Units, responsible for investigating serious sexual offences, were persuading ra</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">pe and sexual assault victims to withdraw their allegations. The reason; to boost their crime figures.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">11). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Across London and doubtless elsewhere, officers normally of Detective Inspector rank, will pour over crime reports ostensibly to supervise them. In </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">actual fact they will be looking to ‘no crime’ or to reduce the classification to a serious offence illustrated above.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Another trick of the trade is to send the statutory, ‘We are sorry you have been the victim of crime’ letter and then after the letter ha</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">s been sent, to reclassify the reported crime as ‘no crime.’</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> The victim will still have his crime number in case of an insurance claim.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">12). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ut what of the England and Wales Crime Survey. For this report, around 67,000 households are selected, and then on</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">e person from each of those household. A letter is sent and then, if the householder responds, the household visited by a BMRB (British </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Market Research Bureau) researcher who asks questions of one household member in relation to them being victims of crime</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">13). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">So, how likely is it that households on recession hit, gang dominated housing estates will invite BMRB researchers into their homes to discuss local crime. Will the drug dealers on those estates speak candidly to BMRB researchers about  being the vi</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ctim of ‘run ups’ an all </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">too</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> common crime in these </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">areas where one drug dealer is r</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">obbed of his drug</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">s or cash  by others.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">  </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">14). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Those working deep within the world of underprivileged youth will tell you that many stabbings and shootings remain unreported.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> Since hospitals have been required to report all knife and gun wound admissions (and many still don’t) a street level expertise has built up around the ‘self treatment’ of knife wounds with superglue while a cottage industry has emerged whereby both quali</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">fied and unqualified back street doctors and nurses treat gunshot and knife woun</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ds</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><a name="_GingerSentBM_358_1"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">15). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Of course </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">further down the scale, </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">every minor act of graffiti is a crime, every </span></a><a name="_GingerWordBM_46_0"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">drugs</span></a><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> deal (of which here are probably tens of thousands every day) is a crime, everyo</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ne who p</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ossesses drugs com</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">mits a crime. I’ve received dozens of</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> emailed requests in</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> the last five</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> months</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> ostensibly from </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Paypal</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ttempting to obtain my details and of course </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">each one is technically a crime. Every other similar phishing attempt to extract </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ccount details is a crime, every act of shoplifting is a crime.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span><a name="_GingerSentBM_359_0"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Of course, mercifully for the government, these crimes will </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">frequently go un</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">reported.</span></a><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">16). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">It doesn’t say much for our modern society that these days, even medium sized stores have security guards but even where a shoplifter is unlucky enough to be caught, it is likely that that apprehension will merely be a blip in his or her career. For many s</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">tores, big and small, the effort of embarking on a prosecution which could end up at Crown Court is simply not cost effective. Many major stores will merely apprehend the suspect, reclaim the goods and ban that individual from the store.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">17). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">The most re</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">cent British Retail Crime Survey suggests that retail crime has increased by a huge 15.6% and that most disturbingly; only one in eight shoplifting offences are actually reported to police. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">18). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Police have increased their target response times in line wi</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">th police cuts which means that in the mayhem of Friday and Saturday nights, the incident will </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">probably </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">be over and the victim gone by the time officers arrive. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">19). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Where </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">police arrive when the incident is in progress the response is often to give indivi</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">duals involved</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> a fixed penalty notice </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">rather than to arrest them for a serious offence in order that those </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">same </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">hard pressed</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> officers can remain out on the streets</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> and continue to deal with incidents</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> Thus again the result is a clear distortion of actual c</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">rime figures. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">20). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Police chiefs will certainly be aware, as are politicians, that the public will be more willing to accept cuts if they </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">believe crime is being reduced. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">21). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">he sad fact of policing today is the fact that</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> quite simply, nowhere for offic</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ers to go if they are concerned with either poor operational decisions, facts being concealed from the public or even dubious practices that border on corruption.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">22). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">They are told to ‘go through channels’ but if there is no c</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">onfidence in senior </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">management or force</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">  Professional Standards Departments then the only option is ‘whistle-blowing.’ </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Sadly police officers are not permitted to directly </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">contact</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> the IPCC. </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Only the bravest or very foolish police officer would now go </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">down the ‘whistle-blowing’ </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">road as there is currently what can only be described as a witch hunt against anyone who has spoken ‘out of turn’ to the media. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">23). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Rather like priests and nurses, those officers who do ‘go through channels’ to report concerns are likely to encounter a </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ess than </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">subtle and indeed sinister  form of intimidation which is aimed </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">against anyone who fails to toe the ‘party line’ or who rocks the boat. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">24). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Police parlance in relation to ‘getting shafted’ or ‘doing his or her legs’ is just as common now as it e</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">ver was and refers to police managers taking ‘unofficial’ revenge on the unfortunate officer who is considered to have not ‘toed the line.’</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">25). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">The recommendation by </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Lord </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">Leveson</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">, that officer</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> are allocated a hotline to report concerns to are greeted wit</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">h derision. Many officers will refuse to complete anonymous staff satisfaction surveys such is their distrust of senior managers. Those surveys in most forces show a staggering lack of confidence in senior management. (see </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">What do they know website</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">’</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> and s</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">earch on police staff surveys). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">26). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">All this is compounded now by what appears to be a witch hunt in respect of any officer who may have made some form of ‘non-corrupt’ contact with the media.  Rank and file officers agree that the Met and police service</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> in general are on the verge of a very real crisis.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">27). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">With the national debt increasing, the recession continuing and life becoming ever more difficult, especially for those in deprived areas where gangs and criminality flourish, the </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">dubious </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">asse</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">rtions </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">of continuing success in terms of police numbers and crime figures will</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt"> count for nothing if we once again stand on the precipice of even more serious disorder than we saw during those terrible days in August 2011. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">28</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">). </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">The bottom line is that whether cri</span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">me is falling or not, the actual number of crimes being committed is far, far higher than government ministers or senior police </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">officers would have us believe-but of course falling crime is good news for both election prospects, promotion prospects and of </span><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">course honours. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:'Courier New'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>